### [Exodus Chapter 19](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#001.md)

[Exodus 19:1](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#001.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_001">exo 19:1</span></span>

In the third month

At Sinai Israel learned the lessons:

\(1\) of the holiness of Jehovah through the Commandments;

\(2\) of their own sinfulness and weakness through failure;

\(3\) and of the goodness of Jehovah through the provision of priesthood
and sacrifice. The Christian learns through the experience of ([Rom
7:7-24](../../../bib/kjv/rom007.htm#007).md) what Israel learned at Sinai.
This division of Exodus should be read in light of; ([Rom
3:19-27](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#019).md); ([Rom
7:7-24](../../../bib/kjv/rom007.htm#007).md); ([Gal
4:1-3](../../../bib/kjv/gal004.htm#001).md); ([Gal
3:6-25](../../../bib/kjv/gal003.htm#006).md) explains the relation of the
law to the Abrahamic Covenant:

\(1\) the law cannot disannul that covenant;

\(2\) it was "added" to convict of sin;

\(3\) it was a child-leader unto Christ;

\(4\) it was but preparatory discipline "till the Seed should come."

third month

That is, June.

[Exodus 19:3](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#003.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_003">exo 19:3</span></span>

Thus shalt thou say

It is exceedingly important to observe:

\(1\) that Jehovah reminded the people that hitherto they had been the
objects of His free grace;

\(2\) that the law is not proposed as a means of life, but as a means by
which Israel might become "a peculiar treasure" and a "kingdom of
priests";

\(3\) that the law was not imposed until it had been proposed and
voluntarily accepted. The principle is stated in ([Gal
5:1-4](../../../bib/kjv/gal005.htm#001).md).

[Exodus 19:5](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#005.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_005">exo 19:5</span></span>

if ye will obey

(Cf) ([Pe1 2:9](../../../bib/kjv/pe1002.htm#009).md); ([Rev
1:6](../../../bib/kjv/rev001.htm#006).md); ([Rev
5:10](../../../bib/kjv/rev005.htm#010).md). What, under law, was condition,
is under grace, freely given to every believer. The "if" of ([Exo
19:5](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#005).md) is the essence of law as a
method of divine dealing, and the fundamental reason why "the law made
nothing perfect"; ([Rom 8:3](../../../bib/kjv/rom008.htm#003).md); ([Heb
7:18](../../../bib/kjv/heb007.htm#018).md); ([Heb
7:19](../../../bib/kjv/heb007.htm#019).md).

The Abrahamic: (See Scofield) - ([Gen
15:18](../../../bib/kjv/gen015.htm#018)) and New (See Scofield.md) - ([Heb
8:8](../../../bib/kjv/heb008.htm#008).md) covenants minister salvation and
assurance because they impose but one condition, faith.

[Exodus 19:8](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#008.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_008">exo 19:8</span></span>

we will do

The Fifth Dispensation: Law. This dispensation extends from Sinai to
Calvary -- from Exodus to the Cross. The history of Israel in the
wilderness and in the land is one long record of the violation of the
law. The testing of the nation by law ended in the judgment of the
Captivities, but the dispensation itself ended at the Cross.

\(1\) Man's state at the beginning ([Exo
19:1-4](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#001).md).

\(2\) His responsibility ([Exo 19:5](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#005).md);
([Exo 19:6](../../../bib/kjv/exo019.htm#006).md); ([Rom
10:5](../../../bib/kjv/rom010.htm#005).md).

\(3\) His failure ([Kg2 17:7-17](../../../bib/kjv/kg2017.htm#007).md);
([Kg2 17:19](../../../bib/kjv/kg2017.htm#019).md); ([Act
